  footnotes: []
english:
  title: A Self-Portrait
  author: Seok Won-gam
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Time slips away with such haste—
    old age and sickness are constant companions.
    My crooked leg leans upon its staff,
    my withered frame grows smaller still.

    Too much leisure breeds only idleness;
    the monk's simple meal brings no weight to these bones.
    As day fades, I eat my rough barley gruel,
    spring has passed and I still wear my patched robe.

    Poverty keeps my brothers few,
    the city's distance thins the worldly ties.
    My sole companion is a solitary cloud
    that drifts now and then beneath my eaves to rest.
  footnotes:
    - The speaker is a Buddhist monk reflecting on aging and the austere life of monastic practice
    - The 'patched robe' (누비옷) symbolizes the humble Buddhist garment, worn thin by time
    - The cloud serves as a metaphor for impermanence and the monk's detachment from worldly concerns
